    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:f95210e4-d933-4f37-b94f-a5f2140992e8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 55-year-old man with a sturdy build and a slightly antalgic gait who appears older than his stated age when walking but otherwise looks well cared for and engaged. He often shifts his weight off his right leg when standing and uses the arms of the chair to rise. He describes chronic knee pain that has gradually worsened over several years, with stiffness after sitting, crepitus when climbing stairs, and intermittent swelling after long days on his feet. On examination, he has reduced range of motion of the knee, bony enlargement, and pain that is worse with weight-bearing and improved somewhat with rest.\n\nHe works as a warehouse supervisor, a role that still involves frequent walking across concrete floors, occasional lifting, and repeated stair use. Outside work, {patientName} enjoys fishing, weekend barbecues with friends, and watching local football with his brother. He used to play recreational five-a-side football in his 30s and 40s but stopped because of knee discomfort. He drives to work, has a mostly sedentary commute, and admits that regular exercise has become difficult because activity predictably aggravates his knee pain.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse and remains independent in basic activities, though he has started avoiding kneeling, squatting, and prolonged shopping trips. He reports poor sleep on nights when the knee aches after overuse, and he has become more irritable about the limitations the pain imposes. He is social and practical, with a close circle of family and long-term friends, but lately he turns down outdoor activities that involve uneven ground or extended walking.\n\nHis lifestyle contributes to symptom persistence: he is overweight, eats a convenience-heavy diet during workdays, and drinks alcohol socially on weekends. He does not report current illicit drug use. He wants to stay employed and active enough to travel and spend time outdoors, and he is increasingly concerned that his knee symptoms are progressing faster over the last year."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e4a4591e-a63b-4999-9f58-9db396c8e134",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports a 4-year history of gradually progressive knee pain, worse over the past 12 months, with no single acute inciting event. He recalls several minor sports-related twists to the knee when he was younger and spent many years in physically demanding jobs that required lifting and prolonged standing. He denies inflammatory-type prolonged morning stiffness, fevers, rash, or involvement of multiple small joints. Over-the-counter analgesics provide partial relief, but he now relies on them several times per week.\n\nHis past medical history is notable for essential hypertension and hyperlipidemia, both diagnosed in his late 40s. He has obesity with a BMI in the low 30s and borderline impaired fasting glucose noted on prior primary care visits, though he has not been diagnosed with diabetes. He has never been hospitalized for major cardiac or pulmonary disease. He underwent arthroscopic meniscal debridement of the right knee many years ago after a work-related injury, with good short-term improvement.\n\n{patientName} is a former smoker with an approximately 15 pack-year history, having quit about 8 years ago. He drinks 6-8 alcoholic beverages on some weekends and 1-2 on occasional weekdays. His diet is high in processed foods and sodium, and he exercises inconsistently because knee pain limits walking distance. He remains independent in self-care but notes difficulty with stairs, getting in and out of low chairs, and completing full work shifts without worsening pain and swelling."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
